    "summary": "Prof. dr. Harry W.M. Steinbusch is appointed as Emeritus Professor in Cellular and Translational Neuroscience at University of Maastricht in the Netherlands. Currently, he is the Co-Chair of the IBRO-ECC Mentorship Initiative to train PhD students and postdocs as an international group to write commissioned review articles. He is Founding and Editor-in-Chief of the Journal of Chemical Neuroanatomy, current 2023 SCI: 3.1, JCI: 5.2 by Elsevier, since 1984. He is co-organizer of the Bright Focus Foundation funded Alzheimer Fast Track Annual 3 days\u2019 workshop for young career scientists since 1998. He is Fellow of the Indian Society for Neuroscience. He was involved as Coordinator of the China Scholarship Council PhD Program at UM comprising close to 324 PhD students as of 2023. For international achievements he received the title of Knight in the Order of the Dutch Lion, 2018. Lifetime Achievement Awards were received from the Italian Neuroscience Society, 2017, the South Korean Neuroscience Society, 2018 and the International Society for Serotonin Research, 2018. \nHis research focus is on the neuroanatomical aspects of development and aging in rodents and post-mortem human brain. As general working hypothesis he studies the pre/peri/postnatal stress leading to depression. This could induce early initiation of progression of neurodegeneration like AD. The focus is on the role of the Brainstem in the pathophysiology of AD and the interphase between depression and AD using various techniques, i.e., molecular neurobiology, quantitative neuromorphology, animal behaviour and epigenetics.\nHe has guided 105 Ph.D. students and published 505 papers. His current Hirsch factor is 104, citations without self-citations 39,840, from 2018: 9,558 and M-factor is 2.3. Best Neuroscience Scientists 2023: World place 510, the Netherlands place 10.\nCitation classic with more than 2,000 citations: Steinbusch H.W.M. Distribution of serotonin immunoreactivity in the rat CNS. Neuroscience 6 (1981) 557-618, in the Current Contents/ Life Sciences 32 (1989) 26, p. 17.\nHe has been President of the Neurotoxicity Society.\nFounding Director of the European Graduate School of Neuroscience (EURON), starting 1997, a gathering of 8 universities in the EUregio.\nFounding Director of NENS - Network of European Neuroscience Schools.\nFounding and Full Director of the School for Mental Health and Neuroscience at Maastricht University for 13 years.\nTwice coordinating a Marie Curie Early-Stage Training site. \nCoordinator of an Erasmus Mundus + program between 4 European and 3 Japanese Universities.",
